{"id":14881531,"mediaExerciseId":"2c7606ee-ce50-4f0a-82da-8182b6e068a6","exerciseName":"4","chapterName":"15","chapterTitle":"Raising Capital","groupId":612405,"groupTitle":"Minicase Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":533,"solutions":[{"id":6048256,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this exercise, we are asked to assess the initial public offering (IPO) of Mark Sexton and Todd Story.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"If the company employs a **Dutch auction**, employees should sell their stock in the IPO at the offering price, since if they are kept and sold after the company is publicly traded, the investor may lose out on the opportunity to profit from the sale of their shares.\n\nEmployees should sell their securities and reinvest or redistribute their investments into a diverse portfolio.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"However, when employees are not even optimistic about the company's long-term prospects, or the IPO will not increase the value of their share, it isÂ a good idea to sell shares on the secondary market. It allows investors to generate significant profits in a shorter time. Stock price volatility in the secondary market helps to assess a company correctly.\n","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"**In this problem, it is preferable to sell its shares in the IPO at the offering price.**","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"de36638e-9f72-46e8-ba85-79b45b085d1b","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"total